title: For Sale:  Help oppose bans - support ccw
postcontent:
A Way for Your Voice to be Heard at Speaker Madigan's Public Hearings on Proposed Right to Carry and Other Gun Issues.

Public Invited to Speak and/or File Witness Slips

Speaker Mike Madigan has called for two public hearings for Illinois residents to voice their support  or opposition to proposed Right to Carry legislation.  

This is an opportunity to speak out against a Chicago-style carry law and in support of a fair and reasonable law.  It is also an opportunity to speak against firearm and magazine bans and other firearm related issues.  Please plan to attend one of these meetings and make your voice heard. Seating will be limited so plan to arrive early.

If you cannot attend, please go online and file a witness slip for Feb.19 hearing showing your support or opposition to key firearm related issues. Link for Feb. 22, 2013 hearing.

http://my.ilga.gov/WitnessSlip/Create?committeeHearingId=10447

http://my.ilga.gov/WitnessSlip/Create?committeeHearingId=10464

Instructions on how to fill out the witness slips:
1. Fill out identification information. If you are filing as an individual, enter "NA" for firm/business/agency and also for title.

2. Enter "NA" for "persons, groups, firms represented".

3.  Position.  You will need to enter each subject matter issue you wish to support or oppose. Click on the circle beside your choice of position. (DO NOT USE THE ARROW KEYS, doing so will change your vote - use the scroll bar to navigate around the page).

4. Enter the next item.
Suggested subject matter to enter
Shall issue license carry - proponent
Statewide preemption for license to carry - proponent
May issue License to carry - opponent
Firearm ban - opponent
Magazine ban - opponent
Ammunition ban - opponent
Registration of firearm/magazines - opponent
Banning private sales/transfers of firearms - opponent
One gun a month - opponent
Report lost or stolen firearm - opponent

5. Testimony - check "record of appearance" if you are not giving oral or written testimony.

6.  Please submit only one slip per person.




Don't miss this important opportunity

to be heard!!

Tuesday, Feb. 19, 2013

Noon

Room 114 State Capitol

Springfield, IL

Attendees will be required to show official state identification and pass through strict security.

Friday, Feb. 22, 2013

10:00 a.m.

6th Floor Committee Room, Michael A. Bilandic Bldg.

160 N. LaSalle St

Chicago, IL

title: For Sale:  1960 Ford F100 Short-bed pickup
postcontent:
Selling my 1960 Ford F100 1/2 ton shortbed pickup - it's the "Styleside" model and is in solid drivable condition once the two front tires are replaced - some jerk flattened them this past weekend when I had the truck parked out front

3-speed manual w/ floor shifter (3 speed + granny low), rebuilt 186 HP 292 Y-block 8-cylinder engine, 4-barrel carb, does not smoke/leak. I've done 85-90mph on I25 and I70 before I knew it. Speedo cable needs replaced or repaired as she reads 22-25mph below the speed you're going.

Electrical system is solid and all lights work (after-market fogs, all turn signals, all headlights). Interior cabin light needs replacement/installation. Wipers work, all emblems intact, and the front light frames as well as the dash are powder-coated white. Original headliner is in good condition too.

Front and back glass plus seals are excellent, side windows/vents are cracked but repaired with epoxy and are fully functional - I have been quoted $21/square foot for custom-cut automotive glass to repair all four (plus labor) - estimate is $130-$160 for full replacement and installation of new safety glass.

Original steering wheel with horn that works, all gauges intact and functional (other than noted speedo issue). No radio, though the wiring is there, and the heater blows strong and hot.

Bed is solid with nothing except some very slight surface rust in a couple of tiny spots, wheel wells are generally good, with just a tiny bit of rust-through at the back side of the front wheel wells. 15" alloys with good tires (approx 50% tread remaining) roll straight and true, and the suspension is solid as well.

Just replaced the master cylinder and the master brake cylinder (because I wasn't happy with the braking) and the four drum brakes are solid. Seat could be worked on and potentially replaced with something a little more comfortable.

I have the original tailgate for the truck, though it is detached and in only okay condition...the back "Ford" panel can be cut and remounted in a new frame if you wanted to have it done, saving you the money for buying a replacement.

I've got two leather Audi A4 adjustable heated seats to replace the current seats...the heaters work and are a single-point connector that can be wired into the current 12V wiring harness. Included with the truck, as well as the original seats so you can take your pick.

I've driven her as far as Pueblo, Fort Collins and Greeley and back to Denver on the highway, side roads and dirt roads with no issues...you could too.

Why am I selling her? Got my eye on a '53 Chevy pickup and I just can't get away from those big flared fenders!

Asking $4100 cash or best REASONABLE offer. I have full and clear title in my hand

title: For Sale/Trade:  Early Pre-WWI ERFURT 1912 Luger 9mm
postcontent: Very Early Pre-WWI ERFURT 1912 Military Luger 9mm. Serial # 64xx.  This is a very early Pre-WWI Luger, that, no doubt, saw action later in the “Great War,” and maybe as late as World War II, this 9mm ERFURT Luger has a chamber date of 1912. The Luger has the earlier style of receiver that did not have a stock lug on the backstrap. The pistol has Imperial proofs on the left side of the receiver. Serial numbers on the pistol are matching, the mag is a correct wood-based WWI Un-Numberd magazine there are two magazines. The pistol’s original finish exhibits normal wear for a luger that is 101 years old, and holster wear on the tip of the barrel and the sideplate, overall finish condition is about 70%. The original wooden checkered grips are fairly worn, and are serial numberd to the gun. The bore is great not worn, good rifling remains. There are NO importers markings anywhere on the pistol. This is an honest early military Luger that has not been messed with. The Leather holster is dated 1936 and was made in Berlin, all stiching is tight and no cracks for something that has lasted 77 years. The holster has a name stamped inside the flap it reads P. A. BECKE. The luger tool has a stamped eagle with 63 under it. This will be a nice addition to your luger collection.

The SureFire high-capacity magazine for 5.56x45 mm (.223 Remington) ammunition, is compatible with M4/M16/AR-15 variants and other firearms that accept standard STANAG 4179 magazines. Constructed from Mil-Spec hard-anodized aluminum, they feed smoothly and reliably due to optimal geometry, non-binding coil springs, and ingenious nesting polymer followers. The long-lasting springs are cadmium coated for low friction and excellent corrosion resistance. Magazines require no lubricants and can be easily disassembled without tools for cleaning. SureFire High-Capacity magazines provide distinct tactical advantages: increased initial firepower in ambush situations; fewer reloads overall, which means less downtime and target distraction in a firefight; fast and easy magazine insertion, even with a closed bolt; less bulk compared to drum mags, enabling a normal weapon grip. The 60-round magazine—slightly thinner than two 30-round magazines clipped together and about the same overall length—fits in most dual magazine pouches, eliminating special carry pouches required for drum magazines. SureFire offers a heavy-duty magazine pouch specifically designed for the MAG5-60 that attaches to a MOLLE system vest.

Features
• Compatible with all weapons that accept standard STANAG 4179 compliant magazines
• Reliable functioning due to mechanical simplicity and high-quality non-binding coil springs—no lubricants required
• Long-lasting springs are cadmium coated for low friction and excellent corrosion resistance 
•Easily seated in weapon with bolt forward
• May be kept fully loaded for extended periods without spring fatigue
• Only 1.66" thick, less than two 30-round magazines clipped together
• 60-round magazine is approximately same length as two 30-round magazines clipped together
• 60-round magazine fits in most dual-mag pouches
